===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|magik|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|magique|lang=fro}}, reborrowed from {{etyl|la}} {{term|magice|lang=la}}, borrowed from {{etyl|grc}} {{term|μαγική||magical|tr=magikē|sc=polytonic|lang=grc}} ({{term|τέχνη||art|tr=tekhnē|sc=polytonic|lang=grc}}), derived from {{term|μάγος|tr=magos|sc=polytonic|lang=grc}}, from {{term|magos magus}}, sorcerer, of Iranian origin; akin to Old Persian {{term|𐎶𐎦𐎢𐏁|sc=Xpeo|tr=maguš||sorcerer}}. Displaced native [[Middle English]] {{term|dweomercraft||magic, magic arts|lang=enm}} (from [[Old English]] {{term|dwimor||phantom, illusion|lang=ang}} + {{term|cræft||art|lang=ang}}), [[Old English]] {{term|galdorcræft||magic, enchantment|lang=ang}}, [[Old English]] {{term|drycræft|drȳcræft|magic, sorcery|lang=ang}}.

